[[File:PIA21210 - Satellite Radar Show Complex Set of Faults Moved in 2016 New Zealand Earthquake.jpg|thumb|Satellite radar image showing ground motion effects during the [[2016 Kaikoura earthquake]]]]
{{use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}
[[File:MarlboroughFaultSystem.png|thumb|320px|Map of the [[Marlborough Fault System]]]]
The '''Kekerengu Fault''' is an active dextral (right lateral) strike-slip fault in the northeastern part of South Island, New Zealand. It is closely associated with the [[Hope Fault]] and Jordan Thrust at its south-easternmost edge and likely joins with the [[Clarence Fault]] to form the [[Wairarapa Fault]] offshore in [[Cook Strait]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Zachariasen |first=Judith  |last2=Berryman |first2=Kelvin  |last3=Langridge |first3=Robert  |last4=Prentice |first4=Caro |last5=Rymer |first5=Michael |last6=Stirling |first6=Mark |last7=Villamor |first7=Pilar  |date=2006 |title=Timing of late Holocene surface rupture of the Wairau Fault, Marlborough, New Zealand |url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/pdf/10.1080/00288306.2006.9515156 |journal=New Zealand Journal of Geology and Geophysics |volume=49 |issue=1 |pages=159–174 |doi=10.1080/00288306.2006.9515156}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last=Lensen |first=G.J. |date=1958 |title=Note on fault correlations across Cook Strait |url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/pdf/10.1080/00288306.1958.10423182 |journal=New Zealand Journal of Geology and Geophysics |volume=1 |issue=2 |pages=263–268 |doi=10.1080/00288306.1958.10423182}}</ref>

Early investigations immediately following the 14 November [[2016 Kaikoura earthquake]] indicate that up to {{convert|10|m|ft|abbr=on}} of motion may have occurred on the Kekerengu Fault during the 7.8 magnitude quake.<ref name="Geonet.org.nz">{{Cite web |url=http://info.geonet.org.nz/display/home/2016/11/14/M7.8+Kaikoura+Earthquake%3A+Latest+updates |title=M7.8 Kaikoura Earthquake: Latest updates |last=McBride |first=Sue |publication-date=14 November 2016}}</ref> During this earthquake the offshore continuation of the Kekerengu Fault to the north east, known as the Needles Fault, ruptured as well. [[National Institute of Water and Atmospheric Research|NIWA]] marine geologist Dr Philip Barnes said the length of the Kekerengu–Needles Fault rupture may extend for about {{convert|70|km|mi|abbr=on}}, consisting of {{convert|36|km|mi|abbr=on}} on land and {{convert|34|km|mi|abbr=on}} under the sea.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/86752499/huge-fault-rupture-stretches-34km-offshore-from-kaikoura |title=Huge fault rupture stretches 34km offshore from Kaikoura |work=Stuff |publication-date=23 November 2016 |access-date=24 November 2016}}</ref>

