{{about|sloping structures used in erosion control and fortifications}} [[File:Revetment 2.png|thumb|300px|right|{{center|Asphalt and sandbag revetment with a [[geotextile]] filter}}]]
In [[stream restoration]], [[river engineering]] or [[coastal engineering]], '''revetments''' are sloping structures placed on banks or cliffs in such a way as to absorb the energy of incoming [[water]]. In [[military engineering]] they are structures, again sloped, formed to secure an area from artillery, bombing, or stored explosives. River or coastal revetments are usually built to preserve the existing uses of the shoreline and to protect the slope, as defense against [[erosion]].
==Freshwater revetments== [[File:Sturdy revetments - geograph.org.uk - 1119250.jpg|thumb|left|{{center|Wooden revetments}}]] [[File:Rock armour revetment Hampton-on-Sea.JPG|thumb|right|{{center|Rock armour revetments}}]] [[File:Liliw,Lagunajf5551 01.JPG|thumb|right|Revetment along Oples River ([[Liliw, Laguna]])]]
Many revetments are used to line the banks of freshwater [[rivers]], [[lake]]s, and man-made [[reservoirs]], especially to prevent damage during periods of [[floods]] or heavy seasonal rains (see [[riprap]]). Many materials may be used: wooden piles, loose-piled boulders<ref>Lake Ontario Riparian Alliance. [http://www.loranet.org/faqrevet.htm "Stone Revetments...Frequently Asked Questions."] Accessed 2009-05-25.</ref> or concrete shapes,<ref>[http://www.water-lines.co.uk/index.php?section=252&page=1877 Concrete shaped revetments] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090123212001/http://water-lines.co.uk/index.php?section=252&page=1877 |date=2009-01-23 }}</ref> or more solid banks.
Concrete revetments are the most common type of infrastructure used to control the [[Mississippi River]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/2018/national/mississippi-river-infrastructure/|title=The struggle to control the Mississippi can help us understand the U.S.|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2018-05-18}}</ref> More than {{Convert|1000|miles|km}} of concrete matting has been placed in river bends between [[Cairo, Illinois]] and the [[Gulf of Mexico]] to slow the natural erosion that would otherwise frequently change small parts of the river's course.<ref name=":0" />
==Revetments as coastal defence== Revetments are used as a low-cost solution for coastal erosion defence in areas where crashing waves may otherwise deplete the coastline. Wooden revetments are made of planks laid against wooden frames so that they disrupt the force of the water. Although once popular, the use of wooden revetments has largely been replaced by modern concrete-based defence structures such as [[Tetrapod (structure)|tetrapods]].
{{clear}}
==Tetrapods== [[File:MumbaiCaltroplikeSeashoreDefence.JPG|thumb|right|{{center|Tetrapod revetment along the waterfront at [[Mumbai]]}}]] {{main|Tetrapod (structure)}}
In coastal engineering, a tetrapod is a four-legged [[concrete]] structure used as armour unit on [[Breakwater (structure)|breakwater]]s. The tetrapod's shape is designed to dissipate the force of incoming waves by allowing water to flow around rather than against it, and to reduce displacement by allowing a random distribution of tetrapods to mutually interlock.
{{clear}}
==Fortifications== [[File:Trench construction diagram 1914.png|right|250px|thumb|[[World War I]]: [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|British]] diagram for the construction of revetted trenches - the revetment here is the part forward of the standing soldier.]]
According to the U.S. [[National Park Service]], and referring mostly to their employment in the [[American Civil War]], a revetment is defined as a "[[retaining wall]] constructed to support the interior slope of a [[parapet]]. Made of logs, wood planks, fence rails, [[fascine]]s, [[gabion]]s, hurdles, sods, or stones, the revetment provided additional protection from enemy fire, and, most importantly, kept the interior slope nearly vertical. Stone revetments commonly survive. A few log revetments have been preserved due to high resin pine or cypress and porous sandy soils. After an [[Fortification|entrenchment]] was abandoned, many log or rail revetments were scavenged for other uses, causing the interior slope to slump more quickly. An interior slope will appear more vertical if the parapet eroded with the revetment still in place."<ref name=NPS-MILITARY-EARTHWORK-TERMS>{{cite web |author=U.S. National Park Service |title=Military Earthworks Terms |url=http://www.cr.nps.gov/HPS/hli/currents/earthworks/glossaryQ_Z.htm |accessdate=2009-05-25 }}</ref>
==See also== * [[Revetment (aircraft)]] * [[Riparian zone]] * [[Riparian-zone restoration]] * [[Seawall]] * [[Riprap]]
